# EXAMINING OUTCOME VARIABLES

# This function examines the outcome variables to determine their best treatment in
# the statistical analysis

examine_outcome_variables <- function() {

# A note on organizations:

# The organization_level outcome variables, by definition, collect together individuals from the profile_level who share the same organization.
# Much like in profile level outcome variables, they imply that each organization was an actor involved in the knowledge flow process
# As a result, it is necessary to organize outcome variables to aggregate the roles played of individuals into organizational roles played
# These roles, reporter, assigned_to, and qa_contact, are the same as the profile level
# The distinction lies in the aggregation, which collects multiple reporter roles from different individuals who are part of the same organizatino
# to represent an organizational "actor" level for each role
#
# In order to ensure that there is sufficient variability and meaning to this level, much like the threshold discussed in the profile-level analysis,
# it is necessary to restrict the data to organizations that have sufficient distinct actors--that is, profiles associated with that organization's unique domain id
# The distribution of organizations with different amounts of actors are as follows:
#	Total organizations:						n = 111,047 (100.000%)
#	  Organizations with only one actor:		n =  94,569 ( 85.161%)
#	  Organizations with only two actors:		n =   8,809 (  7.933%)
#     Organizations with only three actors:		n =   2,639 (  2.376%)
#	  Organizations with only four actors:		n =   1,177 (  1.060%)
#	  Organizations with five or more actors:	n =   3,853 (  3.470%)

# It is clear that many organizational identification tokens (domain) simply reflect a profile-level actor value (i.e., there is only one actor in the domain)
# At two actors, slightly less than 8% of organization domain ids are retained, declining rapidly afterwards
# At five or more, we note an increase.  This increase is due to the fact that the domain id token is imprecise and will often match what are known as
# "webmail", or other "non-organizational" domains.  To address this spuriousness in our representation of the organization-level, we use a database of known non-organizational
# domains, that was manually expanded by the researcher, which includes 5490 such domains, along with common variations due to accidental typographical errors during data entry
# Details of domains constrained can be found here: https://github.com/mekkim/Webmail-Domains adapted from https://github.com/tarr11/Webmail-Domains by Douglass Tarr (https://github.com/tarr11 / http://douglastarr.com)
#
# Constraining the organizations retained from the data to exclude known non-organizational domains, the distribution reduces as follows:
#	Total organizations:										n = 111,047 (100.000%)
#  	  Total organizations (minus non-org):						n = 109,366 ( 98.486%)
#	    Organizations (minus non-org) with only one actor:		n =  94,188 ( 84.818%)
#	    Organizations (minus non-org) with only two actors:		n =   8,631 (  7.772%)
#       Organizations (minus non-org) with only three actors:	n =   2,532 (  2.280%)
#	    Organizations (minus non-org) with only four actors:	n =   1,101 (  0.991%)
#	    Organizations (minus non-org) with five or more actors:	n =   2,914 (  2.624%)

# The significant reduction in the five or more actors amount suggests that this constraint significantly improves the validity of the domain identifier
# Future research could improve it further by expanding the list of known non-org domains beyond 5490 entries

# Based on manual examination of the data, it was noted that organizations with two actors show insufficient variability to be meaningfully different from the profile-level
# In some cases, the inclusion of "two" profiles was spurious, where one individual created two accounts with similar but different names.
# In other cases, generic accounts were paired with accounts with set user names under the same organizational domain id
# As it is our purpose to focus on a conservative estimate of organizational action on the knowledge flow and outcome factors in this study, we choose
# a threshold of 3 actors in order to include an organization in the sample
# While this drastically reduces the number of organizations retained to 6,547, the increase in validity is necessary to avoid spurious interpretations

# In order to further improve validity at the organization-level as distinct from other levels, it is also necessary to ensure sufficient variability
# in the roles in which each organization acts.  At the profile level, it was discovered through analysis that the minimum threshold of actions in a given
# role for sufficient degrees of freedom for non-spurious interpretation was 4.
# Introducing this cutoff, the breakdown of organizations with at least three actors, acting in each of the three roles of reporter, assigned_to, and qa_contact at least 4 times
# is as follows:
# Code: org_level %>% select(is_org_domain, all_actors_count, bugs_reported_count, bugs_assigned_to_count, bugs_qa_contact_count) %>%
#					  filter(is_org_domain, all_actors_count>=3L, bugs_[reported | assigned_to | qa_contact]_count >=4L) %>% nrow();
#
# 	Total organizations with three or more actors:								n = 6,547 (100.000%)
#     Organizations that have acted in reporter role at least four times:   	n = 2,338 ( 35.711%)
#     Organizations that have acted in assigned_to role at least four times:	n =   206 (  3.146%
#     Organizations that have acted in qa_contact role at least four times:		n =   42  (  0.642%)

# The numbers clearly show that the subset of organizations that are meaningful actors in the roles of assigned_to and qa_contacdt are very small
# While there is a sufficiently large number of organizations for standard analysis for the reporter role, interpretation of the results of the other roles
# should be handled carefully to avoid over-broad conclusions
#
# It's worth noting that this filtering demonstrates clearly that there are organition-level actors even in the qa_contact role that are well known, including:
# ACM, Adobe, Dreamhost, IBM, Indiana University, MIT, Nokia, Oracle, PHP, Pixar, Qualcomm, Redhat, Sun, University of Calgary, and Yale

# We proceed in discussing the outcome variables in the role order in a manner similar to the profile level, retaining the above constraints




# REPORTER ROLE:
#
#	The reporter creates and submits the "problem knowledge" in the form of a bug report. The reporter is the start point of the knowledge-flow
#   process and our primary role of interest given the research question, particularly at this, the organization-level of analysis
#   As noted at the profile-level, it is the most common organization-level role in the database

# Subset the organizations according to the constraints detailed above, namely:
#    1) Organizations must have at least 3 "members" in order to be retained as distinct from the profile-level of analysis 	-- Constraining variable: all_actors_count 		>= 3
#	 2) Organizations must not be identified by "known non-organizational" domain ids											-- Constraining variable: is_org_domain			== TRUE
#    3) Organizations must have acted in reporter role at least four times														-- Constraining variable: bugs_reported_count 	>= 4

# For brevity, we drop the nomenclature of "at_least_four" that was used in the profile_level analysis code
# It should be understood going forward that "org_level_<ROLE>" implies the above constraints
# As expected, the constraint filtering below reduces the organizations to the desired n = 2,338 as discussed above
# We constrain the org-level data with the following code:

org_level_reporter <- org_level %>% filter(all_actors_count >= 3L, is_org_domain, bugs_reported_count >= 4L);


# Reopening tendencies

# This category of outcome variables tracks how many times each bug the that was created by a profile acting in the reporter role
# was reopened, along with associated contextual summary statistics.
# As with the bug-level "reopened_count", these variables were operationalized as continuous variables and summarized under that assumption

# Since the org-level outcome measures for reopening tendencies are aggregations of the profile-level measures, it stands to reason that the
# constraints at the profile-level will constrain at the org-level as well

# As such, just like at the profile-level, the pure "count" measures of reopening will be biased relative to the number of times each organization
# takes on a given role.  To address this issue, the measures must be adjusted relative to number of times each role was undertaken.
# Therefore, we conclude that the only appropriate measures are percent-based
# That is, for example, percent of bugs reported that were reopened at least once for each organization.  And so on.
#
# As discussed at the profile-level, the aggregation of more bugs reported at the organization level may allow for meaningful consideration
# of the "at_least_twice" and "thrice_or_more" reopening measures, which lacked sufficient power at the profile-level.
#
# Based on this discussion, the summary statistics of the retained variables are as follows:

summary(org_level_reporter$percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_once);
summary(org_level_reporter$percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_twice);
summary(org_level_reporter$percent_bugs_reported_reopened_thrice_or_more);


# Stargazer adds additional values such as N and ST.Dev:
# Text version:
stargazer(select(org_level_reporter, percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_once),  type="text", style="asq");
stargazer(select(org_level_reporter, percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_twice), type="text", style="asq");
stargazer(select(org_level_reporter, percent_bugs_reported_reopened_thrice_or_more), type="text", style="asq");

# HTML version output to file:
org_level_reporter_percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_once_summary_table	<- stargazer(select(org_level_reporter, percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_once),  type="html", style="asq");
org_level_reporter_percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_twice_summary_table	<- stargazer(select(org_level_reporter, percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_twice), type="html", style="asq");
org_level_reporter_percent_bugs_reported_reopened_thrice_or_more_summary_table	<- stargazer(select(org_level_reporter, percent_bugs_reported_reopened_thrice_or_more), type="html", style="asq");

write(org_level_reporter_percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_once_summary_table,     "./plots/org_level_reporter_percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_once_summary_table.html");
write(org_level_reporter_percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_twice_summary_table,    "./plots/org_level_reporter_percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_twice_summary_table.html");
write(org_level_reporter_percent_bugs_reported_reopened_thrice_or_more_summary_table,    "./plots/org_level_reporter_percent_bugs_reported_reopened_thrice_or_more_summary_table.html");


# We generate its quantiles at 10% intervals using "type 6" as used by SPSS
# m = p. p[k] = k / (n + 1). Thus p[k] = E[F(x[k])].
# For details see ?quantile in package:stats
# Formula source: Hyndman, R. J. and Fan, Y. (1996) Sample quantiles in statistical packages, American Statistician 50, 361365.

quantile(org_level_reporter$percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_once,     probs=seq(0,1,0.10), na.rm=TRUE, type=6) %>% round(6);
quantile(org_level_reporter$percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_twice,    probs=seq(0,1,0.10), na.rm=TRUE, type=6) %>% round(6);
quantile(org_level_reporter$percent_bugs_reported_reopened_thrice_or_more,    probs=seq(0,1,0.10), na.rm=TRUE, type=6) %>% round(6);


# Skewness & kurtosis values
# Skewness tests symmetry of distribution where closeness to 0 means symmetric, left tail gives negative values, right tail gives positive values
# Kurtosis compares distribution shape to Gaussian ideal where 0 means ideal, flatness gives negative values, peakness gives positive values
# We use type "2" methods for determining skewness & kurtosis as used in SAS & SPSS:
# 	skewness: G_1 = g_1 * sqrt(n(n-1)) / (n-2)
# 	kurtosis: G_2 = ((n+1) g_2 + 6) * (n-1) / ((n-2)(n-3))
#
# Formulae source: D. N. Joanes and C. A. Gill (1998), Comparing measures of sample skewness and kurtosis. The Statistician, 47, 183189.
# Details in ?skewness & ?kurtosis for package:e1071

e1071::skewness(org_level_reporter$percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_once,  na.rm=TRUE, 2);
e1071::kurtosis(org_level_reporter$percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_once,  na.rm=TRUE, 2);
e1071::skewness(org_level_reporter$percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_twice, na.rm=TRUE, 2);
e1071::kurtosis(org_level_reporter$percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_twice, na.rm=TRUE, 2);
e1071::skewness(org_level_reporter$percent_bugs_reported_reopened_thrice_or_more, na.rm=TRUE, 2);
e1071::kurtosis(org_level_reporter$percent_bugs_reported_reopened_thrice_or_more, na.rm=TRUE, 2);


# Producing outputs:

#  percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_once:
#
#	    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.
#	 0.00000 0.00000 0.05604 0.08116 0.13330 0.60000
#
#	 ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#	 Statistic                                     N   Mean  St. Dev.  Min   Max
#	 ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#	 percent_bugs_reported_reopened_at_least_once 2338 0.081  0.098   0.000 0.600
#	 ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
