# Examining the results of the transformations of the outcome variables, we find that, different from the reporter role, the cube root transform with removal of select outliers
# transforms the data into a better normality than log10 + 1 in all three cases.  Given the drastic reduction in n from 2338 & 1264 to 206 & 130, it makes sense that outliers
# would have a stronger influence and select exclusion might improve data normality

# As was the case at the profile-level, we interpret this stronger influence as due to the selection bias inherent in the "assigned_to" role as organizational actors acting in the assigned_to role
# are more likely to have a direct effect on the time to outcome than in a previous role.  Further, as many bugs are never assigned in the first place, the range of
# bugs that will be available for any given organizational actor to act upon in the assigned_to role will also be constrained.  In other words, there are additional unmeasured restrictions
# on the degrees of freedom that are not accounted for in the power (n) alone.
# Similar to at the profile level, we will address these issues as part of the regression analysis, correcting for this issue with hccm() from the package "car" that will adjust for heteroskedasticity
# and with Cook's distance to identify outliers that may be skewing data.  Based on visual inspection of the data, the removal of the lowest 3 and highest 3 outliers should be sufficient.

# In summary, we conclude that the following transformations with post-modeling corrections are appropriate for days to outcome tendencies
# 	(mean_days_to_resolution)^(1/3) 					with outlier deletion & post-modeling correction
#	(days_to_first_assignment_mean)^(1/3) 				with outlier deletion & post-modeling correction
#	(days_from_first_assignment_to_resolution)^(1/3) 	with outlier deletion & post-modeling correction




